%N A394792 Number of positive integers <= n with exactly three odd divisors.
%C A394792 a(n) is also the number of positive integers <= n with 3 partitions into consecutive parts.
%C A394792 a(n) is also the number of positive integers m <= n whose symmetric representation of sigma(m) has 3 subparts.
%C A394792 For a theorem of correspondence between the partitions of n into k consecutive parts and the odd divisors of n see A379630.
%e A394792 The first number with 3 odd divisors is 9 so a(9) = 1.
%e A394792 The second number with 3 odd divisors is 18 so a(18) = 2.
%e A394792 The third number with 3 odd divisors is 25 so a(25) = 3.
%e A394792 The three partitions of 9 into consecutive parts are [9], [5, 4], [4, 3, 2].
%e A394792 The three partitions of 18 into consecutive parts are [18], [7, 6, 5], [6, 5, 4, 3].
%e A394792 The three partitions of 25 into consecutive parts are [25], [13, 12], [7, 6, 5, 4, 3].
%t A394792 seq[n_] := Accumulate[Table[Boole[DivisorSigma[0, k/2^IntegerExponent[k, 2]] == 3], {k, 1, n}]]; seq[100] (* _Amiram Eldar_, Apr 04 2026 *)
%o A394792 (Python)
%o A394792 from math import isqrt
%o A394792 from sympy import primepi
%o A394792 def A394792(n): return 1-(m:=n.bit_length()-1)+sum(primepi(isqrt(n>>i)) for i in range(m)) # _Chai Wah Wu_, Apr 13 2026
